08253nam a22009495i 9780812299571DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122995717 a10.9783/97808122995712doi  a(DE-B1597)577446  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a956.9400492404700aFrom Europe's East to the Middle East :bIsrael's Russian and Polish Lineages /ced. by Taro Tsurumi, Kenneth Moss, Benjamin Nathans. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Imperial and National Crucibles -- tChapter 1. “ Little Russia” in Palestine? Imperial Past, National Future (1860–1948) -- tChapter 2. From Hyphenated Jews to Independent Jews: The Collapse of the Rus sian Empire and the Change in the Relationship Between Jews and Others -- tChapter 3. Jewish Palestine and Eastern Eu rope: I Am in the East and My Heart Is in the West -- tChapter 4. Stateless Nation: A Reciprocal Motif Between Polish Nationalism and Zionism -- tPart II. Groups and Institutions -- tChapter 5. The Paradox of Soviet Influence: The Case of Kibbutz Ha- Shomer Ha-Tsa‘ir from the USSR -- tChapter 6. Triumphs of Conservatism: Beit Yaakov and the Polish Origins of Haredi Girls’ Education in Israel -- tChapter 7. Hasidic Leadership: From Charismatic to Hereditary and Back -- tChapter 8. Connecting Poland and Palestine: The Organizational Model of He-Haluts -- tPart III. Formations of Political Culture -- tChapter 9. Israel’s Polish Heritage -- tChapter 10. Violenceas Political Experience Among Jewish Youth in Interwar Poland -- tChapter 11. From Zionism as Ideology to the Yishuv as Fact: Polish Jewish Re orientations Toward Palestine Within and Beyond Zionism, 1927–1932 -- tChapter 12. Hero Shtetls: Reading Civil War Self- Defense in the Yishuv -- tPart IV. Soviet Interludes -- tChapter 13. American Jews and the Zionist Movements in the Soviet Union: The Joint and He- Haluts in Crimea in the 1920s -- tChapter 14. Refuseniks and Rights Defenders: Jews and the Soviet Dissident Movement -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe overwhelming majority of Jews who laid the foundations of the Israeli state during the first half of the twentieth century came from the Polish lands and the Russian Empire. This is a fact widely known, yet its implications for the history of Israel and the Middle East and, reciprocally, for the history of what was once the demographic heartland of the Jewish diaspora remain surprisingly ill-understood.Through fine-grained analyses of people, texts, movements, and worldviews in motion, the scholars assembled in From Europe's East to the Middle East—hailing from Europe, Israel, Japan, and the United States—rediscover a single transnational Jewish history of surprising connections, ideological cacophony, and entangled fates. Against the view of Israel as an outpost of the West, whether as a beacon of democracy or a creation of colonialism, this volume reveals how profoundly Zionism and Israel were shaped by the assumptions of Polish nationalism, Russian radicalism, and Soviet Communism; the unique ethos of the East European intelligentsia; and the political legacies of civil and national strife in the East European "shatter-zone." Against the view that Zionism effected a complete break from the diaspora that had birthed it, the book sheds new light on the East European sources of phenomena as diverse as Zionist military culture, kibbutz socialism, and ultra-Orthodox education for girls. Finally, it reshapes our understanding of East European Jewish life, from the Tsarist Empire, to independent Poland, to the late Soviet Union. Looking past siloed histories of both Zionism and its opponents in Eastern Europe, the authors reconstruct Zionism's transnational character, charting unexpected continuities across East European and Israeli Jewish life, and revealing how Jews in Eastern Europe grew ever more entangled with the changing realities of Jewish society in Palestine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aWorld History.1 aBartal, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Iris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngel, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalili, Ziva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKijek, Kamil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKálmán, Mihály, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoss, Kenneth B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoss, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNathans, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNathans, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShapira, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilber, Marcos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakao, Chizuko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsurumi, Taro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsurumi, Taro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYona, Rona, econt